    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, but it sounds pretty scary. Is there anything specific in that wording that I should be extra careful about? Like, are there certain parts of that sentence that are \"trap\" phrases or things that could hide unexpected costs? I'm worried about stuff popping up later that I didn't see coming.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, the phrase \"any and all losses... of whatever kind\" is particularly broad because it creates an open-ended liability with no specific monetary cap. You should also pay close attention to the scope of \"connection with,\" as litigants often try to drag a freelancer into covering damages that only tangentially relate to your work. Before signing, you should negotiate to limit this indemnification to only those claims directly caused by your negligence or willful misconduct, and ideally include a liability cap to prevent unexpected financial ruin.",
      "source": "target",
