    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Thanks, that's a good point about the \"any and all\" part. It feels like they could just use that wording to sneak in all sorts of random stuff later on. Do you think there are other ways a company might try to hide these kinds of sneaky or predatory liabilities deep in the fine print? Like, how can I spot those \"hidden\" risks before they hit me?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Besides broad indemnity clauses, look out for bindings that require you to indemnify party for their own employee actions, violate confidentiality agreements, or lack a clear \"exclusive remedy\" preventing lawsuits for the same issue. You should also check if the agreement includes an \"entire agreement\" statement that invalidates past verbal promises, or if it demands full jurisdiction in a far-away location where you can't easily access justice. These hidden traps can create liability that surpasses your actual role and cost, so always red-flag clauses that shift risk entirely onto you without recouping fair compensation for your own legal fees.",
      "source": "target",
